======================================================================
THE STRUCTURAL EXPLANATION
======================================================================

At n=5: tournament on 5 vertices has C(5,3)=10 triples.
Each triple is either a 3-cycle (t₃) or transitive (10-t₃).
t₃ ranges from 0 to 4 (max for n=5).

The 5-cycle structure:
  A directed Hamiltonian cycle on 5 vertices uses all 5 vertices.
  The number of directed 5-cycles in a 5-tournament depends on
  the tournament structure, not just t₃ — but t₃≥3 forces c₅≥1.

WHY t₃=3 forces c₅≥1 at n=5:
  3 directed 3-cycles on C(5,3)=10 triples means 7 transitive triples.
  The 3 cyclic triples create a pattern that, combined with the arc
  directions of the transitive triples, must form at least one
  directed Hamiltonian cycle (5-cycle).

This is related to the 'packing' constraint: 3 triangles in a
tournament on 5 vertices create enough cyclic structure to force
a Hamiltonian cycle.
